&lt;h2 id=&quot;standing-up-a-secure-mosquitto-broker&quot;&gt;Standing Up a Secure Mosquitto Broker&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I will provide a high level overview of the steps to run a secure instance of the broker through an AWS EC2 instance:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 id=&quot;setup-the-ec2-instance&quot;&gt;Setup the EC2 Instance&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;follow the usual steps on the AWS documentation to stand up an EC2 instance of AWS
    &lt;ul&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;expose ports 22, 80, 443, 8883 and 1883 (and custom ICMP to echo request for pinging for debugging purposes)&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;use an existing domain name (or purchase one if you donâ€™t already have one) and go through the domain ownership verification steps&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;generate a Route 53 record that maps the domain to the public IP of the EC2 instance for DNS requests&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;you should now be able to SSH into the EC2 instance&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h4 id=&quot;setup-mosquitto-on-ec2-instance&quot;&gt;Setup Mosquitto on EC2 Instance&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;setup a firewall to expose the MQTT unsecured port (1883) and HTTP (using ufw to allow 1883, 8883 and http)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;install mosquitto and generate TLS certs (use certbot)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;assign the requisite permissions ot the user to access the certs&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;configure user/password authentication for the broker&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;configure mosquitto to use TLS through our new certificates&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;you can now ping the broker locally and remotely&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

